2 SENATE BILL 880
1 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
2 Article – State Personnel and Pensions
3 Section 7–701
4 Annotated Code of Maryland
5 (2024 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
6 BY adding to
7 Article – State Personnel and Pensions
8 Section 7–702
9 Annotated Code of Maryland
10 (2024 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
11 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
12 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
13 Article – State Personnel and Pensions
14 1–101.
15 (a) In this Division I of this article the following words have the meanings
16 indicated.
17 (f) Unless expressly provided otherwise, “Department” means the Department of
18 Budget and Management.
19 (j) “Position” means an employment assignment of duties and responsibilities
20 that requires the full–time employment of one individual or less than full–time employment
21 of one or more individuals.
22 7–701.
23 (a) [In] EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN § 7–702 OF THIS SUBTITLE, IN this [title]
24 SUBTITLE, “part–time employee” means an employee who works an average of 50% or more
25 but less than 100% of the regular workweek.
26 (b) An individual who is a full–time employee who is qualified for or desires to be
27 a full–time employee may not be required to accept part–time employment as a condition
28 of continued or new State employment.
29 (c) An individual who is a part–time employee who is qualified for or desires to
30 be a part–time employee may not be required to accept full–time employment as a condition
31 of continued or new State employment.
32 (d) (1) In accordance with regulations adopted by the Secretary, a part–time
33 employee is entitled to receive all employment rights, privileges, and benefits that are
34 normally available to a full–time employee in a similar position with a similar grade and
35 length of service.

SENATE BILL 880 3
1 (2) Benefits shall be prorated in proportion to the number of hours
2 employed.
3 7–702.
4 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
5 INDICATED.
6 (2) “PART–TIME EMPLOYEE” MEANS AN EMPLOYEE WHO WORKS LESS
7 THAN 100% OF FULL–TIME EMPLOYMENT AND WHOSE POSITION DUTIES:
8 (I) DO NOT STEM FROM A PARENT OR ORIGINATING POSITION
9 IDENTIFICATION NUMBER; AND
10 (II) ARE NOT MEANT TO BE SHARED WITH ANOTHER EMPLOYEE.
11 (3) “PROGRAM” MEANS THE PART–TIME STATE EMPLOYMENT
12 PILOT PROGRAM.
13 (B) THERE IS A PART–TIME STATE EMPLOYMENT PILOT PROGRAM IN THE
14 DEPARTMENT.
15 (C) THE PURPOSE OF THE PROGRAM IS TO PROMOTE AND SUPPORT THE
16 INCLUSIVITY OF STATE EMPLOYMENT BY INCREASING THE AVAILABILITY OF
17 PART–TIME POSITIONS WITH BENEFITS IN STATE GOVERNMENT.
18 (D) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL SELECT FIVE AGENCIES IN THE EXECUTIVE
19 BRANCH OF STATE GOVERNMENT WITH A BROAD AND DIVERSE REPRESENTATION
20 OF POSITIONS AND POSITION RESPONSIBILITIES TO PARTICIPATE IN THE PROGRAM.
21 (E) (1) EACH STATE AGENCY SELECTED BY THE DEPARTMENT SHALL
22 EVALUATE FULL–TIME POSITION VACANCIES WITHIN THE AGENCY AS THE
23 POSITIONS BECOME AVAILABLE TO DETERMINE WHETHER ANY OF THE VACANT
24 FULL–TIME POSITIONS COULD BE CONVERTED TO TWO PART–TIME POSITIONS WITH
25 BENEFITS.
26 (2) IF A STATE AGENCY DETERMINES THAT THERE ARE NO VACANT
27 FULL–TIME POSITIONS WITHIN THE AGENCY THAT ARE ELIGIBLE FOR CONVERSION
28 TO TWO PART–TIME POSITIONS, THE AGENCY SHALL DOCUMENT THE REASONS FOR
29 THE DETERMINATION.
30 (F) IF A STATE AGENCY DETERMINES THAT A VACANT FULL–TIME POSITION
31 IS ELIGIBLE FOR CONVERSION TO TWO PART–TIME POSITIONS, THE AGENCY SHALL:

4 SENATE BILL 880
1 (1) CONVERT THE FULL–TIME POSITION TO TWO PART–TIME
2 POSITIONS; AND
3 (2) ADVERTISE AND RECRUIT FOR THE VACANCY AS TWO PART–TIME
4 POSITIONS.
5 (G) IN ADDITION TO EVALUATING VACANT FULL–TIME POSITIONS AS
6 REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (E)(1) OF THIS SECTION, A STATE AGENCY
7 SELECTED BY THE DEPARTMENT FOR PARTICIPATION IN THE PROGRAM MAY
8 EVALUATE ANY OTHER FULL–TIME POSITIONS FOR POTENTIAL SUITABILITY FOR
9 CONVERSION TO TWO PART–TIME POSITIONS.
10 (H) A SUPERVISOR WHOSE DUTIES NORMALLY INCLUDE SUPERVISING AN
11 INDIVIDUAL IN A FULL–TIME POSITION THAT IS CONVERTED TO TWO PART–TIME
12 POSITIONS UNDER THE PROGRAM MAY NOT HAVE THEIR SUPERVISORY DUTIES
13 INCREASED BY MORE THAN ONE INDIVIDUAL AS A RESULT OF THE CONVERSION OF
14 FULL–TIME POSITIONS.
15 (I) ON OR BEFORE JULY 1 AND DECEMBER 1 EACH YEAR, BEGINNING
16 DECEMBER 1, 2026, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL SUBMIT A REPORT TO THE
17 GOVERNOR AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT
18 ARTICLE, THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY ON:
19 (1) THE STATUS OF THE ELIGIBILITY DETERMINATIONS BY EACH
20 STATE AGENCY PARTICIPATING IN THE PROGRAM; AND
21 (2) THE NUMBER OF NEW PART–TIME EMPLOYEES HIRED BY EACH
22 STATE AGENCY PARTICIPATING IN THE PROGRAM.
23 (a) There is a Workgroup for an Inclusive State Workplace.
24 (b) The Workgroup consists of the following members:
25 (1) the Secretary of Budget and Management, or the Secretary’s designee;
26 (2) the Comptroller, or the Comptroller’s designee;
27 (3) the Secretary of Information Technology, or the Secretary’s designee;
28 (4) the Secretary of Commerce, or the Secretary’s designee;
29 (5) the Secretary of Aging, or the Secretary’s designee;

SENATE BILL 880 5
1 (6) the Executive Director of the Maryland Commission for Women, or the
2 Executive Director’s designee;
3 (7) the Secretary of Health, or the Secretary’s designee;
4 (8) the Secretary of Disabilities, or the Secretary’s designee;
5 (9) the Secretary of Transportation, or the Secretary’s designee;
6 (10) the Chancellor of the University System of Maryland, or the
7 Chancellor’s designee;
8 (11) one representative from a State employees union, appointed by the
9 Governor;
10 (12) one member of the Senate of Maryland, appointed by the President of
11 the Senate;
12 (13) one member of the House of Delegates, appointed by the Speaker of the
13 House; and
14 (14) any representative appointed by the Governor under subsection (c) of
15 this section.
16 (c) The Governor may appoint the following members to the Workgroup:
17 (1) a representative who is actively engaged in the caregiving community;
18 (2) a representative who is actively engaged in the disabilities community;
19 (3) a representative who is actively engaged in the healthcare community;
20 (4) a representative who is actively engaged in the older adult community;
21 and
22 (5) an economist with expertise in labor economics.
23 (d) The Governor shall designate the chair of the Workgroup.
24 (e) The Department of Budget and Management shall provide staff for the
25 Workgroup.
26 (f) A member of the Workgroup:
27 (1) may not receive compensation as a member of the Workgroup; but

6 SENATE BILL 880
1 (2) is entitled to reimbursement for expenses under the Standard State
2 Travel Regulations, as provided in the State budget.
3 (g) (1) The Workgroup shall begin meeting before October 1, 2026.
4 (2) The Workgroup shall:
5 (i) outline the steps the State needs to take to encourage the
6 expansion of part–time employment within the State Personnel Management System, the
7 University System of Maryland, and the Department of Transportation;
8 (ii) focus on the inclusive employment opportunities in State
9 government and removing obstacles for individuals challenged by full–time employment;
10 (iii) review the current policies and procedures concerning part–time
11 employment in State government;
12 (iv) analyze the budgetary incentives, recruitment best practices,
13 and support structures currently in place to encourage hiring of part–time, benefit–eligible
14 employees;
15 (v) study the economic and operational effects and quantify the
16 long–term economic benefits of part–time employment on households and State
17 government;
18 (vi) suggest timelines and identify methods and associated metrics
19 for expanding part–time employment opportunities; and
20 (vii) identify any potential statutory changes required to implement
21 the steps identified by the Workgroup.
22 (h) On or before September 15, 2027, the Workgroup shall provide its findings
23 and recommendations in a report to the General Assembly, in accordance with § 2–1257 of
24 the State Government Article.
25 (i) On or before December 31, 2027, the Department of Budget and Management
26 shall develop and distribute guidance to State agencies on expanding part–time
27 employment opportunities, taking into consideration the findings and recommendations of
28 the Workgroup.
29 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
30 1, 2026. It shall remain effective for a period of 3 2 years and, at the end of June 30, 2029
31 2028, this Act, with no further action required by the General Assembly, shall be abrogated
32 and of no further force and effect.

